# StringBuilder vs StringBuffer
  Both are used to create mutable strings (i.e., strings that can be changed).

| Feature         | `StringBuilder`          | `StringBuffer`          |
| --------------- | ------------------------ | ----------------------- |
| Thread Safety   | ❌ Not thread-safe        | ✅ Thread-safe           |
| Performance     | 🚀 Faster                | 🐢 Slower               |
| Synchronization | ❌ No                     | ✅ Yes                   |
| Introduced In   | Java 5                   | Java 1.0                |
| Use Case        | Single-threaded programs | Multi-threaded programs |

StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
sb.append(" World");
System.out.println(sb);  //   Hello World 
---
StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer("Hello");
sb.append(" World");
System.out.println(sb);  // Hello World

## 🔹 Why `StringBuilder` is Faster?
* No synchronization(Multiple threads can access at the same time)
* Less overhead → better performance

## 🔹 Why `StringBuffer` is Safer?
* Methods are **synchronized(Only one thread can access a resource at a time)
* Safe when multiple threads access the same object

